#1 Stage IIIB (T3, N2a, M0) adenocarcinoma of the colon
I had the discussion regarding adjuvant therapy for stage III colon cancer and stated that has been shown to improve disease-free survival as well as overall survival in patients with stage III colon cancer.  I did explain our preferred regimen is FOLFOX and explained the details of FOLFOX with oxaliplatin given on day one and 5-FU given day one as well as the infusion of the pump for days one and two.  This is given every two-weeks for a total of 12 cycles.  I did go over the potential side-effects of 5-FU to include but not limited to nausea, vomiting, hand-foot syndrome, mouth sores, and main side-effects of oxaliplatin which include but not limited to acute and chronic sensory neuropathy.
The patient wishes to proceed with adjuvant therapy.  We will have a port placed next week, and we will plan on beginning chemotherapy the first week in August.  I answered all questions the patient had about his cancer.
#2 Type-2 diabetes
At the current time, he is on oral agents only for his type-2 diabetes.  He is on glimepiride.  I did explain that this has the potential to make him hypoglycemic if he is not eating well due to the chemotherapy.  He does check his blood sugars quite frequently, and so I recommend he continue to do this while on the chemotherapy.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.

[end section id="20112"]

