[start section id="20103"]

Reverend Hunter is a very pleasant 60-year-old gentleman whose oncologic history is as follows:
1.  2007 - Colonoscopy performed negative, suboptimal preparation.
2.  June 11, 2010 - Due to continued anemia, underwent a colonoscopy which noted an ulcerated mass between the appendiceal orifice and the ileocecal valve measuring 5 x 4-cm.  This was biopsy positive for adenocarcinoma.
3.  June 14, 2010 - CT chest, abdomen, and pelvis noted soft-tissue thickening of the cecum.  Some regional lymphadenopathy identified with the largest node being 1.7 x 1.7-cm.
4.  June 23, 2010 - Dr. Mcdermott performed a right hemicolectomy.  Pathology revealed a 3.8- x 3.6- x 1.0-cm tumor which invaded into the pericolic fat.  Per operative report, there was no evidence of intraabdominal spread or other abnormality.  Pathology of the tissue positive for moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma grade 3 (of 4) located in the cecum.   Tumor invades through the muscularis propria into pericolonic fat.  Negative surgical margins.  Of 43 regional lymph nodes removed, five were involved by metastatic adenocarcinoma with extranodal extension.  Stage IIIB (T3, N2a, M0).  CEA level at the time of diagnosis was 6.8, and postoperative CEA level on July 21, 2010, was 1.6.
Interval history:  Mr. Hunter is here to discuss further management of his stage III colon cancer.  Overall, he has recovered from his surgery quite well.  He has got minimal pain and discomfort.  He is eating and drinking normally.  Normal urination.  He has no new physical complaints today.

[end section id="20103"]

